Optimal anti-rotational design in blades typically uses an offset of **3 mm** or less to balance rigidity and stress distribution. Exceeding this (e.g., 5–6 mm) risks warping or structural weakness, while offsets under 2 mm may be too minimal for effective retention. Industry standards (e.g., for turbine blades) often cite **3 mm** as a practical upper limit.
